OL,3,CWhy do people stalk? From 'goal
OL,4,Corientation' to 'addiction'
OL,6,FLast year more than 2,600 convictions
OL,7,Fwere handed out for stalking. But the
OL,8,Ftrue number of those committing the
OL,9,Foffence is likely to be a lot higher,
OL,10,Fwith 1.4 million reporting falling
OL,11,Fvictim to the crime last year alone.
OL,13,FStalking can take many forms, from
OL,14,Fsmall unwanted gifts and repeated,
OL,15,Funwanted messages to sinister
OL,16,Fstakeouts.
OL,18,FExperts liken being a victim of the
OL,19,Fcrime to serving a prison sentence,
OL,20,Fexplaining: "It traps victims
OL,21,Fcompletely within their lives."
OL,26,@|D@MOU}D@_O]
OL,1,W~s1j5 hw1~k4~c1 hw}h7}j7}      G1/10
